```

`test_passes` starts as `false` (RED). After implementation, verify with `cargo test` and set to `true` (GREEN).

The contract (`contract_code`) MUST be a `///` doc-comment on the function signature with all four layers: `user_expectation:`, `pre:`/`post:`, `[P{N}] Goal:`, and `[P{N}] Constraining:`. It is written before any test code.

The `// REQ:` comment in tests MUST be the first line of the test function body or a comment immediately above the `#[test]` attribute, and MUST reference the same `P{N}-{domain}-{operation}` ID as the contract.

## Constraints

- **Contract first, test second, implementation third.** Per Testing Discipline §6.3 and Process Rule P1. The contract is the specification of the test.
- Exactly ONE contract, ONE test, ONE behavior. Minimal implementation.
- The contract must include all four layers: `user_expectation:` (verbal, user's voice), `[P{N}] Goal:` (exactly one justifying principle), `[P{N}] Constraining:` (zero to many constraint principles), and `pre:`/`post:` (behavioral specification).
- The `contract_id` must use `P{N}-{domain}-{operation}` format with the goal principle encoded in the `P{N}` prefix.
- Test must fail before implementation is added.
- Implementation must be the minimum to satisfy the contract without violating constraining principles.
- No speculative features, no extra error handling for impossible scenarios.
- The `contract_code` and `test_code` both carry the same `P{N}-{domain}-{operation}` contract ID.
- The contract must use `/// REQ:` doc-comment format.
- Do not execute arbitrary Python code in Jinja2 expressions (sandboxed execution).
- Preserve the original prompt structure and formatting.
- Handle missing variables gracefully (leave as-is or use default if specified).

